{{nihongo|'''Ōsumi Kurumazuka Kofun'''|大住車塚古墳|}} is a [[Kofun period]] [[Kofun|keyhole-shaped Kofun]], located in the Ōsumi-Hachiōji neighborhood of the city of [[Kyōtanabe, Kyoto]] in the [[Kansai region]] of [[Japan]]. The tumulus was designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1974.<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/401/1731|title= 大住車塚古墳|language=ja |publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs |access-date=August 20, 2023}}</ref>
The Ōsumi Kurumazuka Kofun is a {{nihongo|''{{ill|zenpō-kōhō-fun|lt=zenpō-kōhō-fun|ja|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=}}''|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun}}, which is shaped like two co-joined rectangles when viewed from above. It is located in the gently sloping [[paddy field|rice fields]] on the west bank of the [[Kizu River]]. It was built during the early to middle Kofun period, from the end of the 4th century to the beginning of the 5th century. The total length of the tumulus is approximately 65 meters, the width at the rear is approximately 35 meters, and the width at the front facing northwest is approximately 18 meters. There are traces of a moat around the periphery, and the outer circumference is a rectangle approximately 60 meters wide and approximately 100 meters long. ''[[Fukiishi]]'' has been confirmed on the mound. The [[burial chamber]] is thought to be a pit-style stone chamber containing a clay coffin, but as its has not been excavated, surviving [[grave goods]] are unknown.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4-311-75040-4}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref> According to legend, this is the tomb of the eighth son of the legendary [[Emperor Keitai]], and it has been subsequently suspected that this legend was an [[Edo period]] fabrication.
The tumulus is about a ten-minute walk from [[Ōsumi Station]] on the [[JR West]] [[Katamachi Line]] ([[Gakkentoshi Line]]).<ref name="Shiseki"/>
