The Ōsumi Kurumazuka Kofun is a {{ill|''{{ill|zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because of the mass replacement error that gets rid of the links like this otherwise|lt=zenpō-kōhō-fun|ja|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōhō-fun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|前方後方墳|lt=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|1=Zenpō-kōhō-fun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=zenpō-kōhō-fun}}, which is shaped like two co-joined rectangles when viewed from above. It is located in the gently sloping [[paddy field|rice fields]] on the west bank of the [[Kizu River]]. It was built during the early to middle Kofun period, from the end of the 4th century to the beginning of the 5th century. The total length of the tumulus is approximately 65 meters, the width at the rear is approximately 35 meters, and the width at the front facing northwest is approximately 18 meters. There are traces of a moat around the periphery, and the outer circumference is a rectangle approximately 60 meters wide and approximately 100 meters long. ''[[Fukiishi]]'' has been confirmed on the mound. The [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]] is thought to be a pit-style stone chamber containing a clay coffin, but as its has not been excavated, surviving [[grave goods]] are unknown.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4-311-75040-4}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref> According to legend, this is the tomb of the eighth son of the legendary [[:en:Emperor Keitai|Emperor Keitai]], and it has been subsequently suspected that this legend was an [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] fabrication.
The tumulus is about a ten-minute walk from [[:en:Ōsumi Station|Ōsumi Station]] on the [[JR West]] [[Katamachi Line]] ([[:en:Gakkentoshi Line|Gakkentoshi Line]]).<ref name="Shiseki"/>
